// 📚 synth proposals. Dry-run: uv run tools/verify_claims.py .team/proposed/synth.jsonl
// Deliberately EIGHT (5 + 3 in round 2). My own cross-audit condemns a ledger padded with easy
// claims, so each of these either (a) pins an external fact no existing claim covers, or (b) guards
// a sentence that was DEMONSTRABLY WRONG at HEAD and would regress silently. One is a positive
// control, required by the negative it partners. Nothing here is a verb-exists probe.
{"id": "synth-packer-shell-page-documents-skip-clean-default", "kind": "cli-help", "argv": ["curl", "-sS", "https://developer.hashicorp.com/packer/docs/provisioners/shell"], "expect": "clean scripts from the system", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "CONFLICT L3, resolved. Packer's shell-provisioner page DOES state skip_clean's default ('This defaults to false (clean scripts from the system)'). It does NOT state one for use_env_var_file -- the field 13-build-secrets.md's whole design turns on. This claim pins the half that is documented; the undocumented half is OQ-24, and 11-sources.md now says 'inference', not 'citation'. The negative half is NOT expressible as a claim today: no doc oracle covers developer.hashicorp.com, and every must_fail literal I could pick would be a strawman I invented rather than a sentence the page would print. See OQ-26."}
{"id": "synth-tart-licensing-says-4-hosts-for-orchard", "kind": "doc-contains", "site": "tart", "page": "/licensing/", "expect": "4 hosts for Orchard", "file": "specs/macos-ci/10-tart-vs-utm-adr.md", "claim": "CONFLICT L5. tart.run/licensing states the free-tier Orchard ceiling as '4 hosts for Orchard' in its opening paragraph and as '4 Orchard Workers' in its tier table. A host is not a worker. This claim pins the first phrasing; tart-free-tier-100-cores-4-workers pins the second. Together they prove the page is internally inconsistent -- neither alone does. The ADR's fleet plan is under either reading, so G4's recommendation is unchanged; a reader sizing a fleet AT the ceiling must not treat the units as interchangeable."}
{"id": "synth-00-overview-credits-13-to-secrets", "kind": "file-line", "target": "specs/macos-ci/00-overview.md", "line": 58, "expect": "| `13-build-secrets.md` | secrets |", "file": "specs/macos-ci/00-overview.md", "claim": "D3, fixed and guarded. 00-overview.md's file map credited 13-build-secrets.md to owner 'harness'; the roster says 'secrets'. The orientation doc is the first file a newcomer reads and the last one anyone re-checks, which is how this survived a full cross-check pass. Pinned by line so it cannot drift back."}
{"id": "synth-00-overview-grades-match-11-sources", "kind": "file-line", "target": "specs/macos-ci/00-overview.md", "line": 56, "expect": "graded meaty/thin/cited-as-exclusion", "file": "specs/macos-ci/00-overview.md", "claim": "CONFLICT L2, fixed and guarded. 00-overview.md advertised a '404' grade for 11-sources.md; 11-sources.md defines exactly three grades and states outright that no [404] grade exists because nothing is dead. A direct contradiction between two files the same agent owns. The '404' grade was G10 residue: it existed only because the brief believed four URLs were dead. Pinned so the retracted grade cannot reappear."}
{"id": "synth-07-appendix-declares-no-dead-links", "kind": "file-contains", "target": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "expect": "## Dead links — none", "file": "specs/macos-ci/00-overview.md", "claim": "CONFLICT L1, fixed and guarded. 00-overview.md:52 restated RETRACTED G10 as fact ('4 pruned dead URLs'). There are none: 07-utm-settings-appendix.md is literally headed '## Dead links -- none', and 11-sources.md carries the full G10 retraction. Every downstream file had been fixed; the orientation file had not. This claim ties 00's new sentence to 07's actual heading, so if 07 ever regains a dead-links section the overview's denial fails loudly instead of drifting."}
// --- Round 2: backing the G14 and master-brief retractions added to 11-sources.md ---
// `synth-justfile-has-no-doctor-recipe` is a NEGATIVE over a file. Its positive control lives in THIS
// file and probes the SAME substrate (the Justfile), so the pair dry-runs standalone -- controls resolve
// within the ledger being checked. Without it, "no doctor recipe" would pass against a deleted Justfile.
{"id": "synth-packer-version-is-1-15-4", "kind": "cli-help", "argv": ["packer", "version"], "expect": "Packer v1.15.4", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "G14, RETRACTED. The master brief asserted packer was NOT installed. It is, at v1.15.4. 11-sources.md:143 already asserted 'v1.15.4' in prose with no ledger entry behind it; this closes that gap. Stronger than packer-is-installed (expect 'Packer v1.'), which would survive any 1.x. If this fails, the host packer changed and every packer cli-help claim must be re-captured, not trusted -- same role tart-version-is-2-32-1 plays for the 92 tart/utmctl probes."}
{"id": "synth-justfile-has-no-doctor-recipe", "kind": "absent", "target": "Justfile", "expect": "doctor:", "control": "synth-justfile-has-check-recipe", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "G14, second half, RETRACTED. The brief pointed agents at a `just doctor` recipe to install packer. No such recipe exists: `just --summary` lists build-golden check default link-check link-check-fresh link-check-verbose unverified-count verify-claims verify-claims-json verify-no-secrets. Negative evidence, so it names a positive control on the SAME file -- an absent claim passes against a gutted or deleted Justfile, which is the GB4 hazard this very retraction documents."}
{"id": "synth-justfile-has-check-recipe", "kind": "file-contains", "target": "Justfile", "expect": "check: link-check verify-claims unverified-count", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "Positive control for synth-justfile-has-no-doctor-recipe. Proves the probe CAN see: the same Justfile that lacks a `doctor` recipe demonstrably DOES carry the `check` recipe, with its three real prerequisites. If the Justfile were empty or missing, this control fails loudly and the negative above cannot pass vacuously."}
// --- Round 3: human decisions. OQ-20 counterparty, OQ-32 contamination, the two G19-class URLs. ---
// Uses the `http-status`/`http-contains` kinds and the `polarity` field ledger landed for OQ-26/OQ-37.
// Every `polarity: negative` record names a positive control IN THIS FILE, on the same substrate.
{"id": "synth-cirruslabs-announces-openai-acquisition", "kind": "http-contains", "url": "https://cirruslabs.org/", "expect": "Cirrus Labs to join OpenAI", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "OQ-20, acquisition half CONFIRMED. cirruslabs.org publishes 'Cirrus Labs to join OpenAI'. Paired with synth-cirruslabs-announcement-dated-april-2026 for the date. This settles WHO the counterparty is; it settles nothing about who enforces the licence -- see synth-tart-licensing-page-never-mentions-openai, which is why 04 keeps an UNVERIFIED marker on the escalation contact."}
{"id": "synth-cirruslabs-announcement-dated-april-2026", "kind": "http-contains", "url": "https://cirruslabs.org/", "expect": "April 7th, 2026", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "OQ-20. The acquisition announcement is dated April 7th, 2026, by founder Fedor Korotkov. The date is load-bearing: it is what makes tart.run/licensing demonstrably STALE rather than merely silent -- the tier page was not updated in the ~3 months since."}
{"id": "synth-openai-tart-license-is-fsl-1-1", "kind": "http-contains", "url": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openai/tart/main/LICENSE", "expect": "Functional Source License, Version 1.1", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "OQ-20. tart's LICENSE at its new canonical home (openai/tart) is FSL-1.1-ALv2, copyright 2022-2026 OpenAI. Positive control for synth-fsl-text-never-mentions-cores: proves the probe CAN see this URL's body, so 'no cores' cannot pass because the fetch returned nothing."}
{"id": "synth-fsl-text-never-mentions-cores", "kind": "http-contains", "url": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openai/tart/main/LICENSE", "expect": "core", "must_fail": true, "polarity": "negative", "control": "synth-openai-tart-license-is-fsl-1-1", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "OQ-20. The FSL licence TEXT mentions cores ZERO times. The 100-core Free Tier is therefore a GRANT PUBLISHED ON tart.run, not a clause of the licence. Both can be true at once, and conflating them would mean reading a core limit into a document that has none. Negative evidence: controlled by synth-openai-tart-license-is-fsl-1-1 on the same URL."}
{"id": "synth-tart-licensing-still-lists-cirruslabs-contact", "kind": "doc-contains", "site": "tart", "page": "/licensing/", "expect": "licensing@cirruslabs.org", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "OQ-20. tart.run/licensing still names licensing@cirruslabs.org as the contact, post-acquisition. Positive control for synth-tart-licensing-page-never-mentions-openai: proves the page's indexed text is non-empty and readable, so 'no OpenAI' cannot pass against a gutted index entry."}
{"id": "synth-tart-licensing-page-never-mentions-openai", "kind": "doc-contains", "site": "tart", "page": "/licensing/", "expect": "OpenAI", "must_fail": true, "polarity": "negative", "control": "synth-tart-licensing-still-lists-cirruslabs-contact", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "OQ-20, contact half DOUBTFUL. tart.run/licensing mentions OpenAI zero times: it still says Fair Source, still grants the 100-core Free Tier, still lists licensing@cirruslabs.org -- three months after the acquisition announcement. The page is STALE RELATIVE TO THE ACQUISITION. This claim is why 04 must NOT assert who enforces; it marks that UNVERIFIED citing OQ-20."}
{"id": "synth-tart-index-carries-blog-landing-page", "kind": "doc-index", "site": "tart", "expect": "/blog/", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "Positive control for synth-enforcement-press-release-absent-from-tart-index. Proves the tart search-index oracle CAN see blog paths at all -- so the dated post's absence is a real property of the index, not the oracle failing to index /blog/* wholesale."}
{"id": "synth-enforcement-press-release-absent-from-tart-index", "kind": "doc-index", "site": "tart", "expect": "/blog/2025/10/27/press-release-cirrus-labs-successfully-enforces-its-fair-source-license/", "must_fail": true, "polarity": "negative", "control": "synth-tart-index-carries-blog-landing-page", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "A SECOND G19, found this run. The Oct-2025 enforcement press release is the SOLE source for G4's 'enforcement is not theoretical', yet it is absent from tart's search index (which carries /blog/ and /blog/archive/YYYY/ but ZERO /blog/YYYY/MM/DD/ posts) -- while returning HTTP 200 (tart-2025-enforcement-press-release-is-live). Written as must_fail DELIBERATELY: a POSITIVE doc-index claim on this URL would FAIL and read as a fabrication, which is G10 running backwards. Absence from an index refutes only inside that index's domain."}
{"id": "synth-grep-over-cirruslabs-clones-emits-real-paths", "kind": "cli-help", "argv": ["grep", "-rIl", "DiskFormat", "/Users/bossjones/dev/cirruslabs/"], "expect": "/packer-plugin-tart/", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "Positive control for synth-packer-plugin-clone-free-of-fixture-sentinel. Same command SHAPE over the same substrate with a pattern known to match. The literal '/packer-plugin-tart/' is one no grep ERROR path can produce, per the GB1 lesson: a control keyed on a literal an error message also contains ('fatal:', ':') proves nothing. If the clones vanish, this control fails loudly instead of letting the negative pass."}
{"id": "synth-packer-plugin-clone-free-of-fixture-sentinel", "kind": "cli-help", "argv": ["grep", "-rIl", "ghp_FIXTURE_SENTINEL", "/Users/bossjones/dev/cirruslabs/"], "expect": "/packer-plugin-tart/", "must_fail": true, "polarity": "negative", "control": "synth-grep-over-cirruslabs-clones-emits-real-paths", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "OQ-32. The reference clones are FREE of the fixture sentinel this run's own pre_tool_use hook wrote into them. A grep -rIl negative emits ZERO BYTES on a true negative, so no same-argv control is possible (the GB2 shape); the control runs the same shape over the same substrate with a pattern that does match. This is what makes 02:172-177 upheld with NO --exclude-dir=logs: the contamination is gone at the SOURCE, and the spec never had to accommodate a defect in our own tooling."}
// --- Round 4: CONFLICT S3 RETRACTED. I will NOT freeze the 337 count -- see the claim prose below. ---
// The ONE durable fact behind the 337-vs-365 confusion is that a bare-substring `packer` grep also
// matches the HCP Packer namespace. That is a fact about the sitemap's SHAPE, not a count that rots.
{"id": "synth-sitemap-substring-packer-also-matches-hcp-packer", "kind": "cli-help", "argv": ["curl", "-fsSL", "https://developer.hashicorp.com/server-sitemap.xml"], "expect": "<loc>https://developer.hashicorp.com/hcp/docs/packer", "file": "specs/macos-ci/11-sources.md", "claim": "CONFLICT S3, retracted. The sitemap publishes an /hcp/docs/packer/** namespace (HCP Packer, a DIFFERENT PRODUCT). So `grep -o '<loc>[^<]*packer[^<]*</loc>'` returns 365 while the path-anchored `grep -o '<loc>https://developer.hashicorp.com/packer[^<]*</loc>'` returns 337. I wrongly 'retracted' 337 as drifted; the number did not drift, MY QUERY DID. This claim pins the structural cause -- the existence of the HCP namespace -- rather than either total. DELIBERATELY NOT a claim on '337': that count legitimately rots every time HashiCorp ships a docs page, and a claim that fails on a routine upstream edit is rot, not signal. The load-bearing fact (ZERO /packer/integrations entries) is already pinned by g19-packer-integrations-absent-from-hashicorp-sitemap + CONTROL-hashicorp-sitemap-lists-packer-docs, and never depended on any total."}
